 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ufrodlin7th.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Frodlin7th</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 27<br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/7/02 7:38:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=907.topic&index=366>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_die.gif" align=absmiddle>  Sadly....</span><hr size=1> Sadly,<br>
<br>
Those Paladins who have been contributing to this thread don't appear to be satisfied with their amazing increases in power over the last 6-12 months.  They seem to be unsatisfied unless not only do they receive the increases, but that warriors do NOT get anything in return.  <br>
<br>
This is rather disappointing to me, as I've consistently said that Paladins were great assets when they were played as Paladins.  It seems that at least those who have contributed to this thread (except perhaps Menien), th true desire of these Paladins is not to play a Paladin to the greatest extent, but is really to replace warriors, and/or to BE warriors with spells.<br>
<br>
Warrior:<br>
<br>
Focused on one enemy at a time. <br>
<br>
Must KNOW their enemies and select them according to their relative danger to a group<br>
<br>
In the enemies' faces, taunting, taking the beating<br>
<br>
Doing relatively good combat damage, not great but good.<br>
<br>
Must place inherent TRUST in their groups to be aware of surroundings and communicate that to the warrior, to know and take care of heals/mana/crowd control, as the warrior is generally too focused on the task at hand to be concerned with the other factors.<br>
<br>
Warriors historically are the ones who control the direction of groups/raids through target selection, one mob at a time, and devote their full and undivided attention to that task, not concerning themselves with much else.<br>
<br>
Heck, in most situations, I don't even pay attention to my OWN health, because that's not my function in this game, I let my groupmates concern themselves with that.<br>
<br>
<br>
A Paladin on the other hand:<br>
<br>
Must have GREAT situational awareness, and group awareness.   For a Paladin to be devoting his attention to tanking in the same way that a warrior does is depriving the group of the real benefits of a paladin, who excels in MANY areas in a secondary/tertiary role.<br>
<br>
Crowd Control through Root<br>
<br>
Fast aggro/mob turning<br>
<br>
Well timed heals<br>
<br>
Well timed Laying of hands<br>
<br>
Extreme undead damage<br>
<br>
They really do play a different class than warriors, and level up becoming experts in different areas.  No one knows more about mob offensive details than a warrior, no one knows more about mob aggro ranges/bindpoints than a monk or SK, and no one knows more about group fighting situational dynamics like a Paladin or an Enchanter.   <br>
<br>
So, for Paladins who want to abrogate their responsibility of being situation experts and think that the road to power is through tanking, I suggest that you rethink your playstyle, you're wasting your inherent skills, and screwing my game by making me a 2nd rate tank, AND TRYING TO KEEP ME THERE when that's all I've ever focused on from day 1.  Learn how to play a PALADIN. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uglatius2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Glatius2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Seasoned Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 224<br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/7/02 7:38:57 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=907.topic&index=367>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_die.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: I'm confused...</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> It was explained to me that having a main tank who could unerringly control aggro would trivialize almost every end-game encounter, because at that point, it's simply a matter of CH cycling and healing the main tank.<br>
<br>
If true, &quot;fixing&quot; taunt for warriors would break the game. It would be akin to giving paladins a form of defensive discipline.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Significant point here by Aragir.  Unerringly controling aggro would trivialize almost every end-game encounter.  The point isn't to make taunt iron clad.  Rather the point is, Warriors should be able to do their jobs in the mid to high end game using a BROAD range of weapons.  That's not how it is currently.  There is a very finite number of weapons a Warrior will use because these are the only ones that produce enough agro for them to be effective at holding agro.<br>
<br>
There are some really great ratio weapons in the game that a Warrior has to completely pass on because they don't proc some kind of agro generation.  There are some really great ratio weapons in the game that a Warrior has to completely pass on because they aren't fast enough.  This is SOLELY because taunt alone doesn't work worth spit.<br>
<br>
So if the weapon used is so important (and trust me, it is), than either make the weapons common or adjust it so they aren't so important.  Does that make sense?  It really doesn't compute that the success or failure of a raid can hinge on what the MT is carrying in his primary hand.<br>
<br>
And there are really three issues being discussed here.<br>
<br>
First issue:  Improvements to other plate classes have made them more attractive as group tanks.  However, this is at the expense of a Warrior's attraction.  No compensating improvements have been made to Warriors.  Now the other plate classes compete on a more equal footing for group slots (or even a superior footing) yet Warriors can't solo effectively.  Our niche has been encrouged on.<br>
<br>
Second issue:  In the high end game HP/AC, the traditional advantage areas for Warriors, are either meaningless beyond a certain point (AC soft cap) or are greatly watered down by gear useable by a broad range of classes (100 HP items).  Granted we are still the MT for most guilds in most situations, but its easy to see a time when that would not need to be true.   Defensive is really the only advantage we still retain and the value of that is debated by some.<br>
<br>
Third issue:  Taunt has to be enhanced by using selected weapons to work right.  This seems kind of screwy that only rare hard to get weapons would let a Warrior hold agro well in a high end encounter.  Weapons should be an enhancement to a Warrior, not something that makes or breaks them.  Fixing taunt in some way would be one solution.  Another would be to make high agro warrior weapons more common.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ujedediah.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jedediah</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 13<br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/7/02 7:51:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=907.topic&index=368>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_die.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Warriors are whineing too much.  </span><hr size=1> Man, I can't wait til school starts back up for these paladin ranters.  Have you played a warrior to 60?  DO you have any idea what you are talking about?  When a hybrid or tier 1 melee can take damage almost as well as a warrior (disregarding defensive discipline) there is something WRONG.  What else does a warrior bring to the table aside from moderate damage output and their ability to take hits?  Nada, zip, zilch, nothing.  <br>
<br>
This is the thrust of the thread in my opinion, and I'm putting  it here in the hopes that some of the more recent posters will read it, get a clue, and shut the heck up.  <br>
<br>
The warrior's place in the EQ world is slowly, but surely, being usurped by the other melees, with the exception of about 0.5% of encounters (those ones where defensive or evasive can be used to some effect).  Warriors are complaining because A.) until 60, you cannot taunt anything your level or higher, making a warrrior fairly useless until 60, especially in a raid setting, not to mention that to out-taunt most other melee classes you need difficult to attain and hard to find weapons, B.) with the addition of all/all high hp/ac gear, and the discovery of a softcap on AC, most level 60 melees begin to close the gap between themselves and the warrior, in terms of damage mitigation and hp totals, C.)  with the Luclin expansion and the onset of AA points, the gap between the hybrids and the warrior lessened even further, thanks to a poorly thought out ability that only the hybrids gained.  Most warriors would agree that aside from AE taunt, they are focusing MAINLY on getting the Archetype abilities, ALL of which are available to every other melee class.<br>
<br>
<br>
Thanks, please drive through, and pick up your clue at the next window. <p><p>
