<br>
1- Taunting properly requires certain weapons to be effective.<br>
<br>
2- Taunt should work well enough that weapons would be irrelevant.<br>
<br>
3- Being able to taunt really well would break the game.<br>
<br>
<br>
The problem is, if taunt works well enough that weapons are irrelevant, then OF COURSE you're going to use the weapons that taunt the best, thereby being able to taunt REALLY WELL.  And, in the process, breaking the game.<br>
<br>
Basically, 1 above + 2 above = 3 above.  You see my point?<br>
<br>
-Aragir <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uaragirlancot.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aragir Lancot</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 24<br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/7/02 8:18:41 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=907.topic&index=370>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_die.gif" align=absmiddle>  In reply to Frodlin</span><hr size=1> Frodlin,<br>
<br>
The paladins who are contributing to this thread are well aware of the advances in power that our class has recieved over the last 6-12 months.  Some of the paladins who have posted here have not been polite, and for that I apologize, but the overall message is one I don't think you are going to want to hear.<br>
<br>
Over the last 6-12 months, the things that made paladins more powerful were:<br>
<br>
#1 and most important - changes to 2handed weapons damage output.  This change affected warriors as well, and I'm sure warriors with GOOD two handers can still outdamage paladins with the same equipement against LIVE mobs.<br>
<br>
#2 and very helpful indeed - Alternate advancement opportunities.  These have given paladins a HUGE variety of choices.  But they exist for Warriors as well (although evidently warrior class specific AA options aren't as good as Paladin ones.  Can't comment, don't have access to either).<br>
<br>
#3 and also tremendously helpful - Flowing thought items.  These help the warrior only tangentially, and do not, strictly speaking, help the warrior tank better.  However, flowing thought items (and to a lesser extent Focus items and AA abilities) put non-supremely-equipped paladins in a real bind.  As soon as you start spending AApoints, a paladin really needs to choose one of three routes:  Specialist offensive/tanking, Specialist healing, or Generalist.  <br>
The highest end paladins that you compare to your warrior friends are in guilds that can get them equipment (and have AA abilities) that make them able to actually do both Specialist roles at the same time (although I imagine the highest end paladins are focussing on specialist offensive/tanking, but do not know that to be a fact).  Even still, these high end paladins are not on par with your warrior friends, which means that the other 98% of paladins in Everquest will not come close to matching the offensive/tanking abilities of your warrior friends.  Your role is secure except in the case of the MOST advanced paladins.<br>
<br>
Now, as to the differences in play style that you mention between a warrior and a paladin, all of that is true, and very well said.  I think you misunderstand the point of most paladins who have posted here, however.  Very few paladins want to usurp the role of warriors as the most efficient tank.  Those paladins who have asked for abilities which would make that possible have been shouted down repeatedly at Paladins of Norrath, and some of them (like myself) have been educated in the process.<br>
<br>
You are mistaking the position of many paladins who have posted here for something it is not.  The paladins I've read in this thread are pointing out that while Warriors are no longer as much more powerful than hybrids as they used to be, warriors have not in any way been reduced in power, nor have they even remained at a standstill in power.<br>
<br>
In essence, Hybrids have been upgraded by X amount, and warriors have been upgraded by X-1 amount.  Many Paladins believe that this has left the classes much more balanced than they were before.<br>
<br>
-Aragir <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uchavr.showPublicProfile?language=EN>chavr</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/7/02 8:45:29 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=907.topic&index=371>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_die.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: I'm confused...</span><hr size=1> Hi there,<br>
<br>
  I read the original post and thought I'd add in my input.  I've played a paladin and only a paladin since kunark came out.  Let me try to show you the game from my eyes some before I address the issues brought forth.<br>
<br>
  The majority of my play time has been done preluclin.  I took a 3 month break when luclin came out because the game had gotten to me.  It got to me because I loved my class, but my class was woefully underpowered.  <br>
<br>
  I remember the days of being laughed at, yes literally laughed at, when asking for a group.  The days of running to various zones close to my level and looking for a group instead of fighting.  When I did get groups I had to prove my worth quickly or I ran the risk of being bumped for a warrior if they came in zone.  Fortunatly I learned to get the most out of my class and soon I built a reputation that allowed me access to groups, if a warrior wasn't around.  These were dark times indeed.  If not for my fanatical love of my class, and the few bright times in the game I would have given up long ago.  I gave DAoC a whirl and came back once the balance in that game go worse then anything imagined in Everquest.  I got some of the luclin spells and finished up 58-60.  It was like an entire new world for me.  Finally, my class was actually useful for something.  I was able to get groups rather fast and was picked over warriors that were 5 levels lower then me.  I've been passed over for warriors that were 5 levels lower in the past.  With the changes to defense and finally upgrading my armor I can now actually.... tank stuff.  On raids sometimes I am used as a backup tank.  It's such a cool new world let me tell you.  Imagine this one if you can.  In exp groups, if a warrior isn't around lfg, I can now fill that spot.  Yeah, I don't do as much dmg and I can't take dmg as well, but I can somewhat make up for this with my spells.<br>
<br>
  None of this means that because of the way things were previously warriors shouldn't get a needed upgrade.  I understand that the game changes and the classes might have to be revamped some to meet these changes.  It happened for my class this way, and I won't begrudge another class the same thing.  I just hope that any changes that would be considered have been thought thru very, very carefully.  Not only do you have to consider what a change would do for your class, you have to think about how it will affect everyone else.  I know I for one never want this game to treat my class like it has in the past.  <br>
<br>
  Now for what you've listed in your post.  <br>
<br>
  Gear-  I can understand the want/need for more diverse class only gear.  This shouldn't just be for warriors, but all the classes.  Until this happens (if it ever does) then I just keep this in mind.  Just because an item is great for me doesn't mean I'm the only class that can use it.  If someone else says they could use it then I have faith they've looked at the options and it's something they don't have a better option for.  If a warrior says that item-xy is one of the best for him for that slot then he has just as much right to ask for it as I do.  Sure the stats might help me in more ways, but different classes need different stats.  Besides, more loot will drop if I'm patient enough.  There should be more wpns made when this is done to help diversify wpn selection also.<br>
<br>
  Comparing warriors to paladins and shadowknights and then saying warriors are weaker is just not true.  If anything all 3 classes are on an even bar atm, just they have different skills they bring to a group.<br>
<br>
  Need a puller/tank?  Get a SK for some of the best pulling in the game.<br>
<br>
  Need a dps/tank?  Get a warrior.  No one else can do as much damage while taking as much damage.  Warriors are still the most efficient melee in the game.<br>
<br>
  Need a utility/tank?  Get a paladin.  With our broad range of heals and stuns we have a setup for alot of situations.  Yes, we can tank too.<br>
<br>
  <br>
  As you can see, each of the classes does something similar and different then the others.  Depending on what your doing should be the basis for your selection.  <br>
<br>
  Trying to let a ranger tank for anything serious is funny though.  The idea that a ranger can fill in for a plate class is laughable.  Only the *BEST* equipped rangers have the stats for tanking, and then it's more a novelty then anything else.  Yes, rangers can dish out huge damage now, but allowing them to tank is one of the best ways to spend mana I know of.  Rogues and rangers bleed.  They bleed bad.  If you have to let one of them tank then you have one happy cleric, cause he'll be busy.  Before the ranges go and get mad at me, I do realize that there are some situations where a ranger can do more then just deal damage.  I also know that those situations are a rarity and that overall, my assesment of rangers is accurate.<br>
<br>
  If warriors have a broken aa skill (flurry?) or two then they should try to get it fixed.  As Aragir stated, increasing a classes ability to taunt is tantamount to destroying the game.  Trust me, us paladins have talked post upon post about taunt and how it affects the game and our roles.  If war taunt was increased so they could lock down any mob they wanted then the game would become warped.  Tactics would change swiftly and mobs would become jokes.  In exp warriors taunt just fine.  If somone is drawing agro they shouldn't then that person needs to learn how to work in a group.  Agro managment is something everyone has to do.  <br>
<br>
  When you talk about crits/crips being eyecandy remember something.  Eyecandy is simply that.  It is not something that groups use when selecting a party member.  Yeah, it may have been cool to be the only class with crits/crips, but it was not a defining ability.  Just because others get it doesn't mean your class is now weaker.  It's just eyecandy.<br>
<br>
  Don't worry so much about Slay Undead skill.  Until they come out with an expansion that is made up entirely of undead mobs there won't be that much use for the skill.  This is an eyecandy skill more then anything.  Unless a paladin is soloing in one of like 4 spots for undead at 60, then SU will not have that much affect.  If a paladin is soloing then there is one less person competing for a group.  Yeah, it looks like a really neat skill, but on the whole it's just a flashy cool thing.<br>
<br>
  As someone pointed out, warriors get CA and CS.  Yes, other classes can get it, but in the end it still makes warriors better tanks also.<br>
<br>
  The reason warriors didn't get upgraded is because they were so far ahead of everyone.  Actually, with AA skills, ya'll did get an upgrade.  Anyway, let me try to put it like this.  <br>
<br>
 Imagine if you will a swim team.  There is one guy on the team who is good at every single event.  The coach works with jon until he is the best at every event.  While this is happening the coach has not worked with the bob and larry that are only good at the crawl and at the backstroke.  Well the coach see's that he's neglected his other swimmers so he starts working with them.  Pretty soon bob is able to equal, sometimes beat, jon at the crawl.  Larry is able to do the same with the backstroke.  So now jon is only the absolute best at the breaststroke and butterfly.  Larry and bob can take jon's place at the crawl and backstroke if needed.  Jon is still your overall best choice to use, but if he isn't there for somereason the others can somewhat fill in.  Does this mean that the coach needs to work with jon more to make him the best at it all, making it so the other swimmers are second rate again?  No, it just means that now there is more then one option for who fills the slots come race day. <p>Chavr Wyrmbane<br>
60 Crusader<br>
